    <stitle>INTERNATIONAL&#174; VT 365 DIESEL ENGINE - POWER CYLINDERS - Removal</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>Removal</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Before removing pistons, rings, and connecting rods, remove the following components:</para>
                    <randlist type="bullet">
                        <item>
                            <para>Fuel Filter and Lines</para>
                            <para>See "Fuel System."</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>VGT</para>
                            <para>See "VGT Electronically Controlled Turbocharger."</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Electronic Control Module (ECM), Injector Driver Module (IDM) and Mounting Bracket
                            </para>
                            <para>See "Engine Electrical."</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Glow Plug Relay and Bracket</para>
                            <para>See "Engine Electrical."</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Intake Manifold</para>
                            <para>See "Manifolds and Exhaust Gas Recirculation (EGR)."</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Cylinder Heads</para>
                            <para>See "Cylinder Head and Valve Train."</para>
                        </item>
                    </randlist>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
        <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="6">
            <title>Connecting Rod and Piston Assembly</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Before removing piston and connecting rod assemblies, piston protrusion should be evaluated.
                        This will help identify bent or twisted connecting rods.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f2650701" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd04/D0413.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Figure 258. Checking piston protrusion</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f2350724">Check piston protrusion above crankcase</hotlnk>
                    as follows:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Zero Dial Indicator with Magnetic Base on crankcase deck surface.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Position dial indicator tip onto piston head at the 3 or 9 o'clock position.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Bar crankshaft to measure maximum piston protrusion.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Record reading.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Reposition dial indicator tip onto piston head at the 9 o'clock position.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Record reading, then average the two readings.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f2650702" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd04/D0407.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Figure 259. Side clearance check for connecting rod</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Feeler gauge</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rods</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1 id="S23507001">
                <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge to check connecting rod side clearance as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Pry apart a pair of connecting rods on a crankshaft rod journal. Insert largest
                        feeler gauge to check clearance.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Repeat for each pair of connecting rods on each crankshaft rod journal and compare
                        with specification .
                    </para>
                    <para>Lack of clearance could indicate a damaged rod or a rod bearing out of position. Excessive
                        clearance may require replacement of rods or crankshaft. Correct as required.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent engine damage, check for carbon ridge on top of the cylinder bore, before removing
                        the rod and piston assemblies.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Scrape carbon ridge from top of cylinder bore, if necessary.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f2650703" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd04/D0418.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Figure 260. Connecting rods</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod bolt</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod cap</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Crankshaft</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate crankshaft to position journals for removal of connecting rod assemblies. Mark
                    connecting rod locations.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent engine damage, check connecting rod bolts for binding. If binding exists, check
                        threads carefully.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f2650704" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd07/D0706.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Figure 261. Connecting rod cap bolts</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod cap (8)</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Connecting rod bolt (16)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove two connecting rod bolts and connecting rod cap.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove piston and connecting rod assemblies from crankcase as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Rotate engine into a vertical position.</para>
                    <figure id="f2650705" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../figd04/D0417.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                        <caption>Figure 262. Piston and connecting rod assembly</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Use a wooden or plastic handle to push piston and rod assembly from cylinder bore.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Once piston rings are free of cylinder bore, remove piston and connecting rod
                        assembly from crankcase.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent engine damage, make sure each connecting rod and cap is stamped, marked, or tagged
                        as a matched set.
                    </para>
                    <para>This engine uses fractured connecting rods. Do not alter or damage the fractured mating
                        surfaces of the rod and cap.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f2650706" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd04/D0412.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Figure 263. Cap and rod numbers</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Matching numbers</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Make sure matching connecting rod and cap numbers stay together as a set. A cap from one
                    connecting rod is not interchangeable with any other connecting rod.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
